			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Reasonable expected twist?<a name="27847"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Mar 15 04 2:40 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">I have recently been pondering the utility of weaving 4 or 5 songs into a twist though.</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />

<br />
Oh definitely.  Sometimes it makes all the sense in the world.  When you're chant kiting, you get your maximum efficiency by having Assonance running and coming as close as you can to 4x active chants.
<br />

<br />

<br />
The question you need to ask is:  does the benefit I get from having the 4th song in the mix outweigh the loss of the other three for half a tick each (or thereabouts).  To give an extreme example -- against dragons, you want to keep a resist song going at all times.  Depending on your group makeup, your other two songs might be Muse, Marr or Zek.  If you try to squeeze all three in, resists may drops for 3 seconds here and there.  If the dragon AEs during one of those 3 second increments and people don't resist, you are likely much worse off than you would be had you stuck with resist and 2 other songs.
<br />

<br />
By contrast, if you're twisting DOTs and one drops, that's just 3 seconds less damage.  More than offset by having an extra DOT running most of the time.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"></span></td>
