			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Reasonable expected twist?<a name="28049"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Mar 16 04 10:08 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>You're absolutely correct.  Sometimes you need to be slowing and/or snaring.  At later levels you'd find that you need to be casting more mob focused spells and fewer buffs in some situations -- you'll get Occlusion of Sound (later Harmony of Sound) which is a massive unresistable debuff and better slows and better mezzes etc.
<br />

<br />
Choose whatever produces the best overall benefit for the group.  If snaring a mob means it doesn't run and bring back 6 adds, then snaring &gt; the 3rd group buff.  If occluding a mob means the shaman's slow lands, then occlusion &gt; the 3rd group buff.  If chain mezzing a cleric mob means it doesn't complete heal, then mez &gt; all 3 group buffs.
<br />

<br />
It's all situational and it all calls for judgment.
<br />

<br />
If your group is complaining about insufficient buffs in the bard window, explain what you're doing.  If they continue to complain, don't do it for a few pulls and see if they change their minds.  I find this a very effective educational technique :P.  Now the only complaining I get is &quot;Will you please stay on this mob and do whatever you do to stop it from healing?  No need to rush on the next pull . . . . &quot;</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
